[7] Pennsylvania (Lancaster and York counties): mixed flocks
Date: Thu 6 Oct 2022 06:58 EDT
Source: WGAL News [edited]
https://www.wgal.com/article/usda-reports-new-avian-flu-cases-pennsylvania/41528408#


The US Department of Agriculture is reporting new cases of avian flu across the country and in Pennsylvania.

- A backyard chicken flock in East Lampeter Township, Lancaster County, is among the latest to test positive.
- The flock is one of 2 in the Susquehanna Valley to be impacted by the latest outbreak.
- The other flock is a commercial turkey farm in York County with 25 000 birds.

Pennsylvania Farm Bureau leaders say the new outbreak is a reminder of how to stop the virus from spreading. "Make sure you're checking your vehicles on the way in, making sure you're wearing dedicated clothes and shoes, removing those before you leave the premises. You know, just basic, simple but commonsense biosecurity to make sure we don't spread these terrible illnesses which affect birds throughout Pennsylvania," said Grant Gulibon of the Pennsylvania Farm Bureau.

There are currently 18 commercial and 3 backyard poultry flocks in Pennsylvania having tested positive, according to the USDA. About 4.2 million birds have been impacted.

If you suspect live poultry is infected, you are asked to report it to the Pennsylvania Bureau of Animal Health and Diagnostic Service at 717-772-2852. The number is available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. Signs of avian flu in poultry include a lack of energy and appetite.

While avian flu is deadly to birds, it's still safe to eat chickens and eggs. [Products in the commercial line do not enter the US food chain. Individuals may choose to consume their own raised poultry. - Mod.TG]

[Byline: Matt Barcaro]

